Abstract = {{We present the first direct measurements of the terahertz atmospheric
   transmission above Dome A, the highest point on the Antarctic plateau at
   an elevation of 4.1 km. The best-quartile atmospheric transmission
   during the Austral winter is 80\% at a frequency of 661 GHz (453 mu m),
   corresponding to a precipitable water vapor column of 0.1 mm. Daily
   averages as low as 0.025 mm were observed. The Antarctic atmosphere is
   very stable, and excellent observing conditions generally persist for
   many days at a time. The exceptional conditions over the high Antarctic
   plateau open new far-infrared spectral windows to ground-based
   observation. These windows contain important spectral-line diagnostics
   of star formation and the interstellar medium which would otherwise only
   be accessible to airborne or space telescopes.}},
